1. Case Conversion Methods
     
           upper() → Converts to uppercase
           lower() → Converts to lowercase
           title() → Capitalizes first letter of each word
           capitalize() → Capitalizes first character

text = "hello world"

         print(text.upper())       # HELLO WORLD
         print(text.lower())       # hello world
         print(text.title())       # Hello World
         print(text.capitalize())  # Hello world

 2. Trimming / Removing Spaces

           strip() → Removes spaces from both sides
           lstrip() → Removes left spaces
           rstrip() → Removes right spaces

text = "  hello  "

        print(text.strip())   # "hello"

3. Searching & Checking

          find() → Returns index of substring
          index() → Same as find but raises error if not found
          startswith() → Checks prefix
           endswith() → Checks suffix

text = "python programming"

         print(text.find("pro"))        # 7          print(text.startswith("py"))   # True

4. Replacing & Modifying

           replace(old, new) → Replace substring
           split() → Split into list
           join() → Join list into string
           text = "I like Java"

         print(text.replace("Java", "Python"))  # I like Python

words = "a,b,c"

        print(words.split(","))  # ['a', 'b', 'c']

        print("-".join(['a', 'b', 'c']))  # a-b-c

5. Checking String Content

         isalpha() → Only letters
         isdigit() → Only digits
         isalnum() → Letters + digits
         isspace() → Only whitespace

      print("abc".isalpha())   # True

      print("123".isdigit())   # True

      print("abc123".isalnum()) # True

6. Formatting Strings

         format() → Format values
        f-strings (modern and preferred)

name = "John"
age = 25

      print("My name is {} and I am {}".format(name, age))
      print(f"My name is {name} and I am {age}")

7. Counting & Length

      len() → Length of string
      count() → Count occurrences

text = "banana"

       print(len(text))        # 6
       print(text.count("a"))  # 3

8. Changing Case Style

         swapcase() → Upper ↔ lower
         casefold() → Strong lowercase (for comparisons)

text = "Hello"
           print(text.swapcase())  # hELLO


ESCAPE SEQUENCE CHARACTER:

a = "Fethi is a good girl\nbut not a bad girl"   #(\n for new line)

print(a)

a = "Fethi is a good girl\nbut not a bad \"girl\""    #(\"  \" for double quotes)

print(a)

a = 'Fethi is a good girl\nbut not a bad \"girl\"'

a = 'Fethi is a good girl\nbut not a bad \'girl\''

print(a)


Here are some commonly used escape sequence characters in Python:

Escape Sequence	Meaning
\n	               New line
\t	               Tab space
\\	               Backslash (\)
\'	               Single quote
\"	               Double quote
\r	               Carriage return
\b	               Backspace
\f	               Form feed
\v	               Vertical tab


# New line
print("Hello\nWorld")

# Tab space
print("Hello\tWorld")

# Single and double quotes
print('It\'s Python')
print("She said \"Hi\"")

# Backslash
print("C:\\Users\\Mehak")


OUTPUT:
      Hello
      World

      Hello    World

      It's Python
      She said "Hi"
      C:\Users\Mehak

